<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="283" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="283">
A combination of Henry (Thomas J. Henry) and -gnathus, from the Greek gnathos, jaw, in reference to the similarity with species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Plagiognathus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiognathus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Plagiognathus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="283" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="283">
<taxonomicName authority="Schuh &amp; Salas, 2018" authorityName="Schuh &amp; Salas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Henryognathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Henryognathus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Henryognathus</taxonomicName>
falls within the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Plagiognathus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiognathus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Plagiognathus</taxonomicName>
Fieber, as rendered by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh, RT" journalOrPublisher="Cladistics" pageId="8" pageNumber="289" url="https://doi.org/10.1206/0003-0090(2001)266&lt;0001:RONWPF&gt;2.0.CO;2" year="2001">Schuh (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, with the exception of the structure of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
